  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Esau's Wives and Children. His Settlement in the Mountains of Seir. - In the heading (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 36:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") the surname Edom is added to the name Esau, which he received at his birth, because the former became the national designation of his descendants. - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 36:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 36:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The names of Esau's three wives differ from those given in the previous accounts (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 26:34",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 28:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and in one instance the father's name as well. The daughter of Elon the Hittite is called Adah (the ornament), and in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 26:34",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Basmath (the fragrant); the second is called Aholibamah (probably tent-height), the daughter of Anah, daughter, i.e., grand-daughter of Zibeon the Hivite, and in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 26:34",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", Jehudith (the praised or praiseworthy), daughter of Beeri the Hittite; the third, the daughter of Ishmael, is called Basmath here and Mahalath in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 28:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". This difference arose from the fact, that Moses availed himself of genealogical documents for Esau's family and tribe, and inserted them without alteration. It presents no irreconcilable discrepancy, therefore, but may be explained from the ancient custom in the East, of giving surnames, as the Arabs frequently do still, founded upon some important or memorable event in a man's life, which gradually superseded the other name (e.g., the name Edom, as explained in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 25:30",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); whilst as a rule the women received new names when they were married (cf. Chardin, Hengstenberg, Dissertations, vol. ii. p. 223-6). The different names given for the father of Aholibamah or Judith, Hengstenberg explains by referring to the statement in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 36:24",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", that Anah, the son of Zibeon, while watching the asses of his father in the desert, discovered the warm springs (of Calirrhoe), on which he founds the acute conjecture, that from this discovery Anah received the surname Beeri, i.e., spring-man, which so threw his original name into the shade, as to be the only name given in the genealogical table. There is no force in the objection, that according to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 36:25",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Aholibamah was not a daughter of the discoverer of the springs, but of his uncle of the same name. For where is it stated that the Aholibamah mentioned in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 36:25",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " was Esau's wife? And is it a thing unheard of that aunt and niece should have the same name? If Zibeon gave his second son the name of his brother Anah (cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 36:24",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 36:20",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), why could not his son Anah have named his daughter after his cousin, the daughter of his father's brother? The reception of Aholibamah into the list of the Seirite princes is no proof that she was Esau's wife, but may be much more naturally supposed to have arisen from the same (unknown) circumstance as that which caused one of the seats of the Edomitish Alluphim to be called by her name (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 36:41",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). - Lastly, the remaining diversity, viz., that Anah is called a Hivite in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 36:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and a Hittite in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 26:34",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", is not to be explained by the conjecture, that for Hivite we should read Horite, according to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 36:20",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", but by the simple assumption that Hittite is used in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 26:34",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " sensu latiori for Canaanite, according to the analogy of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 1:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 10:29",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 7:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; just as the two Hittite wives of Esau are called daughters of Canaan in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 28:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". For the historical account, the general name Hittite sufficed; but the genealogical list required the special name of the particular branch of the Canaanitish tribes, viz., the Hivites. In just as simple a manner may the introduction of the Hivite Zibeon among the Horites of Seir (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 36:20",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 36:24",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") be explained, viz., on the supposition that the removed to the mountains of Seir, and there became a Horite, i.e., a troglodyte, or dweller in a cave. - The names of Esau's sons occur again in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 1:35",
